   <guid isPermaLink="true">http://www.dw.de/dw/episode/0,,15836180,00.html?maca=en-podcast_living-planet-948-xml-mrss</guid>
   <title>Living Planet: Biking around the world</title>
   <link>http://www.dw.de/dw/episode/0,,15836180,00.html?maca=en-podcast_living-planet-948-xml-mrss</link>
   <description>Biking around the world: our very own cross continental cyclist, London&#039;s Borris bikes, Bogota&#039;s Ciclovia, BASF&#039;s search for efficiency and Beijing&#039;s status envy are all in our look at international attitudes to cycling. We also hear reactions to the partial veto of Brazil&#039;s controversial forestry code.
	You can listen to the show online or subscribe to Living Planet as a podcast. Click on the links below for the individual items. Scroll to the bottom for the full show.
Borris bikes impress LondonersLondon is the most recent city to introduce a program that&#039;s sweeping the world: the public bicycle scheme. Robin Powell reports on how it&#039;s been received, the bumps it&#039;s encountered and where it&#039;s going.
	Report: Robin Powell, London

	
	 

	 

	 

	 
Bogota turns streets to parksThe Colombian capital of Bogotá is chaotic and chronically congested. Probably not the greatest place to ride a bicycle, but on a Sunday this metropolis of more than 8 million people is transformed.
	Report: Nadja Drost, Bogota
A &#039;partial&#039; victory for Brazil&#039;s forestsMilton Bragatti in Sao Paulo reports on President Dilma Rousseff&#039;s decision to partially veto a controversial new forestry code.
	Report: Milton Bragatti, Sao Paulo
From Egypt to South Africa by bikeDW reporter Peter Hille has just completed an enormous cycling tour that took him from the top of Africa to the bottom. DW spoke to him earlier this month while he was still in Namibia and began by asking him to lay out his route.
	Interview: Nathan Witkop / Peter Hille
Bikes&#039; image problem in BeijingIn Beijing, rising affluence has saddled bikes with an image problem that&#039;s proving difficult to shake, despite the clever ideas of some.
	Report: Ruth Kirchner, Beijing

	
	 

	 

	 

	 
BASF&#039;s pro-bike policiesBASF&#039;s sprawling chemical production site in Ludwigshafen, Germany, is a workplace for tens of thousands of people, where moving personnel efficiently means money.
	Report: Kate Hairsine, Ludwigshafen</description>
