  <item>
   <guid isPermaLink="true">http://www.dw.de/dw/episode/0,,15834796,00.html?maca=en-podcast_living-planet-948-xml-mrss</guid>
   <title>Living Planet: For peat&#039;s sake</title>
   <link>http://www.dw.de/dw/episode/0,,15834796,00.html?maca=en-podcast_living-planet-948-xml-mrss</link>
   <description>The eager beavers working to save Ukraine&#039;s peatlands; why some French butchers would prefer their cattle farmers to be a little more British; a cat parasite that may be making many of us worse drivers; and one team&#039;s quest to make fish farming a little cleaner for the environment.
	You can listen to the show online or subscribe to Living Planet as a podcast. Click on the links below for the individual items.
Eager beavers save Ukraine&#039;s peatlandsThe draining and burning of peat bogs may account for up to 6 percent of manmade greenhouse gas emissions, according to a recent UN report. A project in Ukraine is looking to flood and restore thousands of hectares to their natural state.
	Report: Saroja Coelho, Polisia, Ukraine
A French butcher with a taste for British beefTired perhaps of celebrity chefs, France now has a celebrity butcher. His untypical views on French produce are whipping up attention. A steakhouse for which he is butcher recently opened in Paris boasting the best beef in the world… from England.
	Report:  John Laurenson, Paris
Andy Danylchuk&#039;s quest to improve fish farmsAmerican ecologist Andy Danylchuk teamed up with an environmental film-maker to investigate modern fish farming. Fish Meat takes a critical look at large-scale fish farming, but along the way also identifies some traditional operations that offer useful solutions for striking a balance with nature.
	Report: Amy Mayer, Massachusetts, USA
Crazy cat people - just an urban legend?The idea that cats somehow make their owners crazy is a staple of urban legends, but one Czech researcher has made it his mission to prove the link. Jaroslav Flegr thinks a parasite transmitted by cats can cause an array of problems, including schizophrenia.
	Report:Shant Shahrigian, Prague</description>
