  <item>
   <guid isPermaLink="true">http://www.dw.de/dw/episode/0,,15834596,00.html?maca=en-podcast_living-planet-948-xml-mrss</guid>
   <title>Living Planet: Solar dimming</title>
   <link>http://www.dw.de/dw/episode/0,,15834596,00.html?maca=en-podcast_living-planet-948-xml-mrss</link>
   <description>The sun dims for Germany&#039;s solar subsidies; A Latvian invention promises to raise solar efficiency; the cost of extreme weather events rises; La Nina&#039;s toll on Paraguay; and a look at Earth Hour from Berlin.
	You can listen to the show online or subscribe to Living Planet as a podcast. Click on the links below for the individual items.
The sun dims for Germany&#039;s solar subsidiesLast year Germany installed a whopping 7.5 gigawatts of new solar panels. For a country with a third of the sunlight of Spain, the solar industry is booming. Or perhaps bubbling, say its critics. Amid a raft of bankruptcies due to competition and reductions to incentives, is the sun rising or setting on Germany&#039;s solar experiment?
	Report: Jonathan Gifford, Berlin
Coating promises to improve solar panelsLatvia might not spring to mind as a hub for solar technology, but the small Baltic nation may have come up with a technology that could boost solar panel&#039;s efficiency considerably.
	Report:  Ģederts Ģelzis, Riga
La Nina takes toll on ParaguayIn Paraguay, people are suffering from a severe drought. The country is the hardest hit by La Nina in Latin America. Thousands of small farmers’ livelihoods have been affected across the country.
	Report: Sam Cowie, Asuncion
Cost of extreme weather risesLast year was an especially bad year for weather extremes like the drought in Latin America. Reinsurance companies – the companies that insure the insurance industry – have a big stake in keeping track of natural disasters, and they say weather extremes are taking up a growing share of their payouts.
	Report: Fabian Schmidt (presented by Kate Laycock)
Earth Hour from BerlinLast weekend saw millions of people around the world turn off their lights for a symbolic moment. Since 2007, Earth Hour has spread around the world, drawing millions of participants from dozens of countries.
	Interview: Cinnamon Nippard, Berlin</description>
