  <item>
   <guid isPermaLink="true">http://www.dw.de/dw/episode/0,,15834512,00.html?maca=en-podcast_living-planet-948-xml-mrss</guid>
   <title>Living Planet: Under pressure</title>
   <link>http://www.dw.de/dw/episode/0,,15834512,00.html?maca=en-podcast_living-planet-948-xml-mrss</link>
   <description>Stuttgart begins powering cars with food waste; improving Europe&#039;s recycling rates; sticking a face on meat; London hosts &#039;Planet under Pressure&#039;; and an interview on reshaping the UN.
	You can listen to the show online or subscribe to Living Planet as a podcast. Click on the links below for the individual items.
Stuttgart begins powering cars with food wasteA recent study found that Germans throw away an incredible 11 million kilos of food a year. While much of this is turned into compost, German researchers in Stuttgart are trying to find another use for this organic matter. They want to take biowaste from the fruit and vegetable market to power cars with natural gas.
	Report: Kate Hairsine, Stuttgart
Improving European recycling ratesThis week, official figures showed that 25 billion glass bottles and jars were collected for recycling in the EU in 2010, the latest year for available data. That meant glass recycling rates held steady at around 68 percent, according to the European Container Glass Federation. But recycling figures for other waste are much lower. DW spoke to participants of a project aiming to change this.
	Report: Julian Bohne, Hamburg
Dennis Buchmann sticks a face on meatMost of us don&#039;t see the fields where vegetables are grown or the conditions in which animals live before they&#039;re rendered into shrink-wrapped packets of meat in the supermarket. Dennis Buchmann wants to tackle this disconnection. A meat-eater, concerned about animal welfare, his idea is MeineKleineFarm - which means my small farm. He draws attention to meat by giving it a face.
	Report: Cinnamon Nippard, Berlin
&#039;Planet under Pressure&#039; greets AnthropoceneThis week more than 2,800 experts from around the world gathered in London for yet another large environmental conference. The Planet under Pressure meeting aired a slew of proposals and warnings all aimed at steering the direction of this year&#039;s 20-year follow-up to the Rio Earth Summit.
	Report: Robin Powell, London
An interview on reshaping the UNEven to people who don&#039;t track these things closely, it&#039;s clear that two decades of United Nations climate talks have achieved very little. One of the policy briefs presented in London proposes ambitious reforms for international bodies like the UN and World Trade Organisation, to equip them for the 21st century.
	Interview: Frank Biermann / Nathan Witkop</description>
